    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/08-agents-harness/01-tool-use-function-calling.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: The tool schema lives in the model's CONTEXT (read-only input), while the tool CALL is text the model GENERATES \u2014 this asymmetry is the whole mechanism of function calling.; The tool-call loop is a cycle: model call -> if tool calls, execute and append results -> call again; it exits only on a plain-text response or a max-iteration cap, and the message history grows O(n) in the number of calls.; The harness turns raw model text into an executed call via a parse -> validate -> dispatch pipeline, and EVERY failure at every stage takes the same path back to the model: errors are just tool results.; Function calling is a learned META-SKILL taught by SFT with loss only on the assistant turns (the tool-call JSON and the grounded final answer); because the schema is in-context, the skill generalizes to tools never seen in training.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  parse-validate-dispatch-pipeline, sft-loss-masking-tool-use\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
