    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/08-agents-harness/05-agent-memory.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: The two memory horizons: everything INSIDE the context window is available on every token but is finite and costs tokens; everything OUTSIDE persists across sessions and is unbounded but must be explicitly fetched (write/read across the boundary).; Episodic vs semantic memory: timestamped situated events (append-only, grows monotonically, queried by time) versus stable general facts (upserted/overwritten, queried by content) \u2014 and why mixing them into one store poisons retrieval.; The write / read / reflect triad, with REFLECT as the highest-value, most-skipped operation: it distils many noisy episodic records into a few compact high-signal semantic facts.; Memory compaction: the in-context prefix grows unboundedly, so at a threshold the old prefix is replaced by a shorter lossy summary while recent turns are kept verbatim \u2014 recursively (rolling / hierarchical micro+macro), keeping the context bounded regardless of session length.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  agentmem-reflect-distillation, agentmem-compaction-sliding-window\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
