    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/01-foundations/01-linear-algebra.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Matrix multiplication is one computation with three equivalent readings; the outer-product reading expresses C = AB as a sum of rank-1 matrices, which is the conceptual bridge from matmul to low-rank structure.; The SVD factors ANY matrix into rotate-scale-rotate (U, Sigma, V^T): the orthogonal factors U and V preserve lengths and angles, and ALL the stretching lives in Sigma.; A fast-decaying singular-value spectrum means keeping only the top-r rank-1 terms is the BEST rank-r approximation (Eckart-Young), and it captures almost all the signal while the tail is noise \u2014 this is the theoretical heart of the chapter and directly motivates LoRA.; Backprop through a linear map is the transpose rule: dL/dW = X^T G and dL/dX = G W^T. The forward matmul's transposes reappear in the backward pass; this is the single most important identity in deep learning.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  lora-lowrank-bottleneck\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
